03816nam a22004335i 9780804789462DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047894627 a10.1515/97808047894622doi  a(DE-B1597)582378  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aBIO0000002bisacsh1 aAnderson, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGalana :bElephant, Game Domestication, and Cattle on a Kenya Ranch /cMartin Anderson. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (338 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Imagining Africa -- tChapter Two. Safari -- tChapter Three. The Elusive Bongo -- tChapter Four. White Sale -- tChapter Five. Poison Arrows -- tChapter Six. Water Works -- tChapter Seven. Cash Cow -- tChapter Eight. Domesticating Science -- tChapter Nine. The End of Innocence -- tChapter Ten. Year of the Jackhamm -- tChapter Eleven. Sleeping Sickness -- tChapter Twelve. Losing Ground -- tChapter Thirteen. Too Big to Succeed -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn avid sportsman, Martin Anderson first visited Kenya on a hunting safari in 1960, three years before the country gained its independence from English colonial administration. Anxious to return and be a part of Kenya's new beginning and Jomo Kenyata's encouragement of "harambee" (working together with European settlers/farmers), he partnered with a Kenya settler and started to raise cattle. Four years later and with one more partner, he accepted the government's offer to develop a vast tract of raw African bush for a game and cattle ranch. This book is a history of that grand and remarkable journey. Galana recounts the story of the creation, achievements, and demise of the largest cattle ranch in Kenya and perhaps all of Africa. Located on an arid 2,500-square-mile tract—1 percent of all the land in Kenya—the Galana Ranch was founded in 1968. Galana introduced cattle into a region with virulent insect-borne disease, adapted the animals to the land, and bred resistant stock. It conducted scientific research into the domestication of wildlife, and aimed to manage Galana's vast natural population of elephants, lions, rhino, lesser kudu, eland, oryx, and other game to help that population attain a level the land could support. In the 1970s and 80s, however, an epidemic of poaching nearly wiped out Galana's vast elephant herds, and the ranch shut down in 1989. This engrossing memoir goes to the heart of Kenya's wildlife management issues and political challenges through a personal tale of adventure and enterprise in Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aSheldrick, Dame Daphne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478946240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804789462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804789462/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles